Gorenje (GRVG)  Group d.d. dropped the most
in almost six weeks in Ljubljana after owners of the Slovenian
appliance maker shunned the companyâ€™s plan to buy back as much
as 10 percent of outstanding shares.  Gorenje fell 24 cents, or 5.7 percent, to 3.962 euros at
the 12:50 p.m. close of trading in Ljubljana, giving the company
a market value 63 million euros ($82 million). The stock has
lost 21 percent of its value this year compared with a 2.4
percent decline of the benchmark SBITOP index of six-most traded
stocks.  Shareholder of the Velenje-based company on Feb. 3 failed
to approve the proposal to buy back shares that would be used
for a possible takeover or a listing of its stock outside
